Hello, I posted a link below, I think it's quite an interesting topic, I find it amazing how all these 'little' quirks have already been taken care of, but I do believe ( as the thread will discuss ), that what Jeff suggested should be implemented for everyone, I wanted to make myself a Cancelled / Aborted Touch Phase, but Jeff is right, a 'began' event should have a pairing 'ended' event, his solution suggests I believe.. One extra variable in the Touch.as class, perhaps being "interrupted:Boolean" ( default: false ).

Then I believe the onInterruption function will set this variable to true in this little code block:

``` as3
{
        touch.phase = TouchPhase.ENDED;
        touch.interrupted = true;
}
```

you will know better than me where it will be then be reset back to false, but I'm assuming it would be here:

``` as3
// dispatch events
processTouches(mCurrentTouches, mShiftDown, mCtrlDown);
if (mCurrentTouches.length > 0)
{
        // reset interruption on all touches
        for each (var touch:Touch in mCurrentTouches)
        {
            touch.interrupted = false;
        }
}
```

Now I believe if this is all correct so far, an example use case of the new changes would be as follows:

``` as3
public function touchEnded( x_:Number , y_:Number , interrupted_:Boolean = false ):void 
{
        if ( true == interrupted_ ) 
        {
            //do interrupted stuff, in my case, reset actions to a default state, 
            //as if the initial Touch never took place

            return; // this maybe useful, to skip the code below ( below code being normal touchEnded calls
            //do default touchEnded things if the 'touch' was not interrupted
        }
}
```

